(586944, ' Importing a weapon into Pakistan is not impossible but is a very complicated and expensive task.\n\nFirst of all, an idivisual is not allowed to import a weapon but it can be done through an authorized arms dealer holding an import licence. \n\nThe following article taken from "The News" will be quite helpful for some of you and will explain a few things.\n\nref: [URL]http://www.thenews.com.pk/Todays-News-10-131128-NRAP-allowed-duty-free-import-of-weapons[/URL]\n\n\n[B]KARACHI:  The Ministry of Commerce has allowed the National Rifle Association of  Pakistan (NRAP) one time duty-free import of air weapons, air pallets,  and segment models, said a top official. \n[/B] \nJaved Lodhi,  Secretary NRAP, told âThe Newsâ that they have been allowed one-time  duty-free import of air weapons to meet their sports requirement. âIt  includes pallet guns, air weapons, segment model (rifles, pistols,  shotguns) with ammunition,â he added. \n \nâThis decision will  help in the development of shooting as a sport in the country, and  hopefully the ministry will give this permission on annual basis in  future,â he added. \n \nThe secretary further said that air  pallets and air weapons for junior players would arrive in a month.  âThis will help us further our youth development programme. The other  ammunition will be imported according to the requirement of the  associationâs units,â he said. \n \nAll four provinces, Islamabad, and three armed forces are the units of NRAP. \n \n\nIt  must be noted that[B][I] [COLOR=#800000]the association is not allowed to directly import  air weapons[/COLOR][/I][/B], which is hampering their efforts to spread this sport in  the country although Admiral M Asif Sandila, Chief of Naval Staff, is  its president. \n\n \n[B][COLOR=#800000]The secretary said that only arms dealers  are allowed to directly import weapons[/COLOR][/B]. âThe sport is getting popular in  Pakistan. We have recently started training programmes in 40 to 50  schools and colleges, so we are in dire need of equipment,â said the  secretary. \n\n \nâWe have to boost this sport because we have a  lot of talent in it. Besides this direct import issue, [B][COLOR=#800000]we have some 80  percent duties on the import of air weapons[/COLOR][/B], which is another blow to  the sport,â he added. \n\n \nJaved said that without duties one  rifle costs Rs350,000 and pistol costs Rs150,000. â[B][COLOR=#800000]We have 55 percent  duty, 15 percent sales tax, and five percent income tax[/COLOR][/B]. One can guess  how difficult it is for this sport to flourish in the country.â \n\n \n\nHe  claimed that India allocated Rs500 million annually for this sport and  Iran $5 million, but âhere in Pakistan we have annual grant of Rs1.2  million, and out of that Rs0.4 million is spent on paying fees to  international bodies. The amount we need to spend on the preparations of  one shooter is Rs5 million a year,â he said. \n\n\n  [URL="http://www.thenews.com.pk/TodaysPrintWriterName.aspx?ID=10&URL=Waqar%20Hamza"]Waqar Hamza\n[/URL] The News\nMonday, September 10, 2012 \nFrom Print Edition', ''),
